<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-178-508  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 178 508.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Feb 26 1990 v7 n8 p61(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Emerald Bay looks for chance to shine again: upgrade boostsdatabase efficiency. (Ratliff Software Production Inc. upgradingEmerald Bay database engine) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sherer, Paul M.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Ratliff Software Production Inc introduces Emerald Bay 3.1, anupgrade to its database engine that adds several key functions andincreases overall performance.andP;  The new product consists of adatabase engine for storage and retrieval and a set of four'surfaces': Vulcan, a dBASE-like compiler/interpreter; a Lotus1-2-3 add-in that lets users access Emerald Bay from thespreadsheet; and toolkits for writing C and Pascal applications.andO;Each surface includes a copy of the engine, a report writer, andforms-design, data management, and translation utilities.andP;  Ratliffofficials claim that Emerald Bay 2.1 updates databases twice asfast as previous versions.andP;  Each surface sells for $395 and hasenhanced support tools for such functions as repairing damageddatabases.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Ratliff Software Production Inc. (product enhancement).andO;Product:   Emerald Bay 2.1 (Data base management system) (productintroduction).andO;Topic:     Data base management systemsProduct Introduction.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Emerald Bay Looks for Chance To Shine AgainandM;Ratiff Software Production Inc. is prepping its Emerald Bay database enginefor a second shot at the market with an upgrade that boosts overallperformance and adds key functions that were missing in earlier releases.andM;Emerald Bay 2.1, available now from the Montrose, Calif., firm, features afaster and more efficient database server along with a smattering ofenhancements to each of the four &quot;surface&quot; modules that round out the EmeraldBay line, according to Bob Byers, a partner of the firm.andM;The Emerald Bay database system consists of a database engine that handlesbasic storage and retrieval functions, and a set of four surfaces: The VulcandBASE-like interpreter and compiler; a Lotus 1-2-3 add-in that gives thespreadsheet access to Emerald Bay; and two tool kits that let C and Pascaldevelopers write data-handling applications.andM;Each surface comes with a copy of the engine, which supports two users;servers that support more than two users can be purchased at an additionalcost.andM;Accompanying each surface is a report writer, a forms-design utility, atranslation utility, and assorted tools for managing data and maintainingdata integrity.andM;Version 2.1 of the Emerald Bay database server performs database updatestwise as fast as version 2.0, Byers claimed.andP;  The server has also beenmodified to allow Emerald Bay applications to run in the multitaskingDesqview environment from Quarterdeck Office Systems.andM;The new Vulcan 2.1 dBASE-like surface, priced at $395, now enables developersto create mouse-driven applications.andP;  In addition, the 2.1 version compilercreates files that are 10 percent to 15 percent smaller than those createdwith the previous release, Byers said.andM;The 2.1 upgrade of the $395 C Developer's Toolkit adds 30 new functions forscreen management, letting C developers access screen-formatting informationin a database--a task that only the Vulcan surface could perform in previousreleases.andM;The support tools included with the surfaces have also been enhanced: Thedatabase-repair facility, for example, restores corrupted databases twice asfast, on average, Byers claimed.andM;&quot;In the earlier version, it would take hours to rebuild the indexes on acorrupted 100M-byte test database I had,&quot; said John Hey, proprietor of GMTCorp., a software-development and systems-integration company in Greenwood,Miss., and a beta tester of the software.andP;  &quot;Version 2.1 significantly speedsthe indexing process.&quot;andM;The new report writer in Emerald Bay excels in some areas--its ability tosort virtual tables, for example--but lacks important features such as theability to replace characters in the middle of a string, Hey said.andO;</TEXT></DOC>